h6 class="sr-only">ChatGPT said:</h6><div class="text-base my-auto mx-auto [--thread-content-margin:--spacing(4)] @[37rem]:[--thread-content-margin:--spacing(6)] @[72rem]:[--thread-content-margin:--spacing(16)] px-(--thread-content-margin)"><div class="[--thread-content-max-width:32rem] @[34rem]:[--thread-content-max-width:40rem] @[64rem]:[--thread-content-max-width:48rem] mx-auto max-w-(--thread-content-max-width) flex-1 group/turn-messages focus-visible:outline-hidden relative flex w-full min-w-0 flex-col agent-turn" tabindex="-1"><div class="flex max-w-full flex-col grow"><div data-message-author-role="assistant" data-message-id="f77678d2-91d2-4067-bdef-f6dc57b8ab31" dir="auto" class="min-h-8 text-message relative flex w-full flex-col items-end gap-2 text-start break-words whitespace-normal [.text-message+&amp;]:mt-5" data-message-model-slug="gpt-5-mini"><div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1 empty:hidden first:pt-[3px]"><div class="markdown prose dark:prose-invert w-full break-words dark markdown-new-styling"><p data-start="0" data-end="41">Not exactly — let me clarify carefully.</p>
<p data-start="43" data-end="211">Git <strong data-start="47" data-end="94">doesn’t store actual databases or DBMS code</strong> like MySQL server databases. It only tracks <strong data-start="139" data-end="171">files in your project folder</strong>. So here’s what happens in your case:</p>
<hr data-start="213" data-end="216">
<h3 data-start="218" data-end="248"><strong data-start="222" data-end="248">1. What Git will track</strong></h3>
<ul data-start="249" data-end="417">
<li data-start="249" data-end="319">
<p data-start="251" data-end="319">Your <strong data-start="256" data-end="271">SQL scripts</strong>, e.g., <code data-start="279" data-end="298">create_tables.sql</code>, <code data-start="300" data-end="317">insert_data.sql</code></p>
</li>
<li data-start="320" data-end="357">
<p data-start="322" data-end="357">Your <strong data-start="327" data-end="340">Java code</strong>, <code data-start="342" data-end="349">.java</code> files</p>
</li>
<li data-start="358" data-end="417">
<p data-start="360" data-end="417">Any <strong data-start="364" data-end="388">config or text files</strong> inside your project folder</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="419" data-end="511">Git <strong data-start="423" data-end="475">will not automatically track the actual database</strong> you created in MySQL. That means:</p>
<ul data-start="512" data-end="678">
<li data-start="512" data-end="578">
<p data-start="514" data-end="578">Your tables and data in MySQL <strong data-start="544" data-end="575">stay on your local computer</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="579" data-end="678">
<p data-start="581" data-end="678">If someone clones your repo, they won’t get your live database — only the scripts to recreate it.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="680" data-end="683">
<h3 data-start="685" data-end="716"><strong data-start="689" data-end="716">2. Role of <code data-start="702" data-end="714">.gitignore</code></strong></h3>
<p data-start="717" data-end="789"><code data-start="717" data-end="729">.gitignore</code> tells Git <strong data-start="740" data-end="773">which files/folders to ignore</strong>. For example:</p>
<ul data-start="790" data-end="953">
<li data-start="790" data-end="856">
<p data-start="792" data-end="856"><code data-start="792" data-end="817">lib/mysql-connector-j-*</code> → Don’t push MySQL connector library</p>
</li>
<li data-start="857" data-end="903">
<p data-start="859" data-end="903"><code data-start="859" data-end="868">*.class</code> → Don’t push compiled Java files</p>
</li>
<li data-start="904" data-end="953">
<p data-start="906" data-end="953"><code data-start="906" data-end="912">*.db</code> → If you have SQLite or local DB files</p>
</li>
</ul>
<blockquote data-start="955" data-end="1067">
<p data-start="957" data-end="1067">So <code data-start="960" data-end="972">.gitignore</code> <strong data-start="973" data-end="1009">does not save tables or database</strong>. It just prevents Git from uploading unnecessary files.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr data-start="1069" data-end="1072">
